summary.seg: A Tudor part book, which contains the music for one voice over a range of pieces, here, the tenor. It was possibly created in East Anglia for the private chapel of Thomas Fiennes, 9th Baron Dacre. It would originally have formed part of a set of five or perhaps six for individual voices. The accompanying bass part is found in Cambridge, St John's College MS 234, but the others are lost.

Both part books comprise, for their respective voices, the music for 10 individual motets by a range of Tudor composers; three by Robert Fayrfax, two by Stephen Prowett and two by John Taverner, and one by each of H. Davy, Lovell, and Hugh Austen or Aston. There is also a Stabat Mater by Richard Davy, and a Magnificat by Fayrfax. Lastly, the book provides five compositions for the musical accompaniment to the mass: two by Fayrfax, and one of each of Austen, William Pasche, and Thomas Ashwell, making 17 individual pieces in all.

In the heading for Ashwell's mass, a blessing on King Herry, i.e. Henry VIII, is written, on folio 31r, and one motet preserves the name of his first and longest-lasting wife, Katherine of Aragon. Nevertheless, the presence of Taverner's music implies a date later in their marriage, which was annulled in 1533, so likely the manuscript was written between 1524 and that date.

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation in the top right corner of each recto.

collation.p:
The MS consists of 4 quires as follows:
2 modern paper flyleaves
Quires 1-28 (fols 1-16)
4 modern paper flyleaves
Quire 3 8 (fols 17-24)
Quire 410 (fols 25-34)
4 modern paper flyleaves

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in very good condition; some staining particularly to the edges of the final two leaves.

layout.p: 9 lines of text accompanying 9 5-line staves of music.
The staves are ruled in pen and are very regular in appearance. Frame ruling in pencil is visible, for example, in the top right hand corner of folio 17r.

handNote.p: Written in late gothic script by a single scribe.

decoNote.p: Each piece begins with an elaborate large gold initial decorated with red pen work. The initial A to the first piece, on folio 1r has coloured foliate decoration with penwork extending into the upper and left margins of the page.

bindingDesc.p: Early twentieth-century binding with brown buckram over cardboard sewn on eight supports.
The companion partbook, Cambridge, St John's College MS 234, is in its original vellum binding.

origin.origDate: First half of the 16th century C.E. (c. 1524-1533)

provenance.p: The manuscript was owned by John Moore (1646-1714) Moore, John, 1646-1714 , Bishop of Ely. Bishop Moore's collection was donated to the University Library by King George I (1660-1727) George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 in 1715.

Listed in the 1856 catalogue as being bound with CUL MS Dd.13.28, a seventeenth-century legal manuscript which was also from the library of John Moore but the two manuscripts do not appear to have any prior connection.
